income_pop_growth <- gapminder_join %>% 
  select(country, income, population) %>% 
  filter(country=="Qatar" | country=="Luxembourg" | country=="Singapore" | country=="Brunei" | country=="Ireland") %>%
  ggplot(aes(x=income, y=population, color=country, group=country))+

  theme_igray()+

       x = "income",
       y = "population")+
  theme(plot.title = element_text(size = 10, face = "bold"),
        axis.text = element_text(size = 4),
        axis.title = element_text(size = 10))
income_pop_growth

For Singapore and Ireland, as the GDP increases per person, the population increases. Brunei and Luxembourg do not have an increase of population when there is an increase of GDP per person. Qatar has a relatively steady population as GDP per person increases with a huge increase in population between ~110,000 and 130,000 GDP increase per person. This spike might correlate with the spike in income during the 1960s and 1970s.
